the fugal system.

00:01:48.570 --> 00:01:55.230
There are lots of politics
in music especially the types

00:01:55.230 --> 00:01:56.530
of words that we use.

00:01:56.530 --> 00:02:00.810
We talk about mastery of form
and wanting to master the fugue.

00:02:00.810 --> 00:02:04.820
And fugues have often have
this sort of academic,

00:02:04.820 --> 00:02:10.390
like the highest aspiration for
composers that they want to able

00:02:10.390 --> 00:02:14.900
to compose a fugue well, and
they want to be the masters

00:02:14.900 --> 00:02:23.050 position:56%
of the subject with all the answers,
showing off at an exposition,

00:02:23.050 --> 00:02:27.680
in their exposition, swiftly
dealing with any episodes of kind

00:02:27.680 --> 00:02:33.780
of unruly musical characters,
and often finding different ways

00:02:33.780 --> 00:02:37.890
to augment their reputation
especially

00:02:37.890 --> 00:02:41.370
by start doing their stuff
towards the end of the fugue.

00:02:41.370 --> 00:02:43.450
So, I apologize.

00:02:43.450 --> 00:02:45.000
You're going to be
in for tonight but.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:51.420
But how does one manage
this and how does one strive

00:02:51.420 --> 00:02:55.050
to master these types
of things historically?

00:02:55.050 --> 00:02:57.050
Those are questions that we
might just hint at tonight

00:02:57.050 --> 00:02:58.510 position:56%
but we're not going to try to tackle

00:02:58.510 --> 00:03:01.920
because they're very
large types of questions.

00:03:01.920 --> 00:03:10.110
So, in the feudal system-- fugal
system, I'm sorry, you know,

00:03:10.110 --> 00:03:12.850
many people, their eyes glaze
over when you start to get

00:03:12.850 --> 00:03:17.480
into the details of
fugal structures and--

00:03:17.480 --> 00:03:19.560 position:56%
so, we're not going to do that here.

00:03:19.560 --> 00:03:23.220
So instead, we're going
to look specifically

00:03:23.220 --> 00:03:24.950
at where fugues have trod.

00:03:24.950 --> 00:03:29.940
Like what types of
things are we talking

00:03:29.940 --> 00:03:32.010
about when we speak of a fugue?

00:03:32.010 --> 00:03:38.600
Is it the structure of a fugue
that gives its identity as a fugue

00:03:38.600 --> 00:03:41.150
or is there rather a
collection of traits

00:03:41.150 --> 00:03:48.510
or is it some combination
of these things?

00:03:48.510 --> 00:03:51.610
[ Laughter ]

00:03:51.610 --> 00:03:57.780
There is no real perfect
example of what a fugue is.

00:03:57.780 --> 00:04:01.790
Often, it's described as having an
exposition and having other sorts

00:04:01.790 --> 00:04:05.080
of development of qualities
going through episodes

00:04:05.080 --> 00:04:09.820 position:56%
and then coming back to some sort
of summation and a sort of a return,

00:04:09.820 --> 00:04:13.910
in a way that's somewhat
similar to a sonata.

00:04:13.910 --> 00:04:18.680
But, what I would rather
focus on as a listener,

00:04:18.680 --> 00:04:21.800
especially if you're a listener
who's hearing a particular fugue

00:04:21.800 --> 00:04:25.280
for the first time is how is
it that we tend to approach it?

00:04:25.280 --> 00:04:27.090
And there's lots of
different ways and different--

00:04:27.090 --> 00:04:30.520
everybody has a different
approach to it.

00:04:31.910 --> 00:04:36.290
But it's basically-- it's
dependent on the material

00:04:36.290 --> 00:04:40.390 position:56%
that a composer is using, the actual
composer, the particular traits

00:04:40.390 --> 00:04:44.540
of that composer, and the time on
which the composer is writing in.

00:04:44.540 --> 00:04:49.490
Another factor that we're
going to look at in particular

00:04:49.490 --> 00:04:53.320
with the fugues that we're going
to hear today is their location

00:04:53.320 --> 00:04:56.930
with respect to the rest of
the music in the program.

00:04:56.930 --> 00:05:00.170 position:56%
They have basically a locus ultimus.

00:05:00.170 --> 00:05:03.590
They're the last thing
that you hear in each work.

00:05:03.590 --> 00:05:07.100
And I'm talking about the
preludes and fugues in Bach

00:05:07.100 --> 00:05:09.760
from the first book of
"Well-Tempered Clavier."

00:05:09.760 --> 00:05:12.730
It's not fugues and preludes,
it's preludes and fugues.

00:05:12.730 --> 00:05:15.560
So, they're kind of these pairs
where the fugue is the point

00:05:15.560 --> 00:05:17.130
where you're going towards.

00:05:17.130 --> 00:05:19.910
And then in the Beethoven,
the fugue comes

00:05:19.910 --> 00:05:22.970
at the end with some modifications.

00:05:22.970 --> 00:05:27.140
And the same with the Brahms,
the fugue comes at the end.

00:05:27.140 --> 00:05:29.850
But all of them exhibit
certain traits that tend to come

00:05:29.850 --> 00:05:34.380
through quite clearly and these
deal with issues of variation

00:05:34.380 --> 00:05:35.680
that we find in other types

00:05:35.680 --> 00:05:39.910
of [inaudible] strategies
in non-fugue works.

00:05:41.690 --> 00:05:44.280
One thing that I do notice
when I'm listening to a fugue

00:05:44.280 --> 00:05:47.280 position:56%
and I'm just thinking in the
abstract here, that I think in terms

00:05:47.280 --> 00:05:49.730
of voices, like usually
there's a presentation

00:05:49.730 --> 00:05:52.040
of a single idea that I listen to.

00:05:52.040 --> 00:05:54.720
And then I think of them
in terms of layering.

00:05:54.720 --> 00:05:57.390
I may not know at what pitch
level is going to come in next

00:05:57.390 --> 00:06:00.910 position:56%
or something like that, I might
have an idea, but I'll get the sense

00:06:00.910 --> 00:06:04.270
that it's another voice
that's being layered onto it.

00:06:04.270 --> 00:06:08.260
I also get a sense that there's
a limited number of ingredients

00:06:08.260 --> 00:06:10.530
that are going into the
mix that are contributing

00:06:10.530 --> 00:06:14.180
to this musical composition
that I'm hearing.

00:06:14.180 --> 00:06:17.180
But generally, this is the case,
not always the case especially

00:06:17.180 --> 00:06:20.050
in very complicate fugues.

00:06:20.050 --> 00:06:30.210
So, if there is no single real
definition or defining fugue type

00:06:30.210 --> 00:06:33.350
that we can look at, what
do we get when we have--

00:06:33.350 --> 00:06:36.730 position:56%
what can we do about this smaller
versions of fugues that tend to come

00:06:36.730 --> 00:06:40.130
up such as the fugato
and the fughetta.

00:06:41.290 --> 00:06:46.730
There's not much that we can
do except to say-- I'm sorry--

00:06:46.730 --> 00:06:52.830
that there are attempts to
describe the process of the types

00:06:52.830 --> 00:06:57.660 position:56%
of imitation and things that
composers employ at specific moments

00:06:57.660 --> 00:07:03.460
to emulate a strict contrapuntal
style or maybe not so strict,

00:07:03.460 --> 00:07:07.140
just depending on these types of
ingredients that they might use

00:07:07.140 --> 00:07:09.360
that we might recognize
in a fughetta passage.

00:07:09.360 --> 00:07:13.850
It might be in versions,
stretching the themes out a bit

00:07:13.850 --> 00:07:17.280
through what's called augmentation,
contracting them a bit,

00:07:17.280 --> 00:07:20.530
through diminution, all these
different types of things

00:07:20.530 --> 00:07:23.030
that we can still somehow
identify it either

00:07:23.030 --> 00:07:27.600
as more typically significant
or having the similar sort

00:07:27.600 --> 00:07:35.430
of overarching form to it, shape
to the phrase, shape to the motive.

00:07:35.430 --> 00:07:38.940
Still assuming like it's
very much a part of it.

00:07:40.470 --> 00:07:43.160
But specifically looking
at tonight's and we won't--

00:07:43.160 --> 00:07:44.910
don't worry, we won't be
spending a ton of time

00:07:44.910 --> 00:07:47.140
with keys and stuff like that.

00:07:47.140 --> 00:07:51.550
But there is-- the way that the
program is constructed is really

00:07:51.550 --> 00:07:58.530
nice, I think, and
augmentatious, as I put it.

00:07:58.530 --> 00:08:03.640
We have what is essentially
a kind of one way

00:08:03.640 --> 00:08:07.300
of putting these different
preludes and fugues in order

00:08:07.300 --> 00:08:10.760
that is not the way that you see
it in the "Well-Tempered Clavier."

00:08:10.760 --> 00:08:15.320 position:56%
So, when Bach first was putting
these together and did the fair copy

00:08:15.320 --> 00:08:19.960
in the 1722, the way
that it was ordered

00:08:19.960 --> 00:08:21.810
in terms of keys is progressive.

00:08:21.810 --> 00:08:24.910
That is, it gets start with
C and then we move to--

00:08:24.910 --> 00:08:29.750
