until we get to B. It's a--

00:08:29.750 --> 00:08:33.090
It's not maybe the way that you
would encounter it in performance

00:08:33.090 --> 00:08:35.930
and in fact, you probably
would not have encountered it

00:08:35.930 --> 00:08:39.010 position:56%
as an entire block in a performance.

00:08:39.010 --> 00:08:42.720
So, oftentimes, what is--
pianists have their opportunity

00:08:42.720 --> 00:08:45.890
or keyboardists I should say
have the opportunity to put them

00:08:45.890 --> 00:08:49.740
in particular orders that make
sense, and this one does to me.

00:08:49.740 --> 00:08:52.320
And we'll listen a little bit

00:08:52.320 --> 00:08:56.600
to hear why it might
make sense as well.

00:08:56.600 --> 00:09:00.410
So, in this case, we start with
A-flat major and then if we go

00:09:00.410 --> 00:09:02.920
down a fifth-- I'm
calling it a fifth--

00:09:02.920 --> 00:09:04.510
that would give us D-flat major.

00:09:04.510 --> 00:09:07.550
But then, we'll give it the minor,
well, so, say, D-flat minor.

00:09:07.550 --> 00:09:10.990
And then, we'll enharmonically
change that to C-sharp minor.

00:09:10.990 --> 00:09:14.220 position:56%
So, it kind of works out as a fifth.

00:09:14.220 --> 00:09:16.860
And then if we go down, if you
give me that, we go down a fifth

00:09:16.860 --> 00:09:23.820
from there to F-sharp major, and
then if we take the relative minor

00:09:23.820 --> 00:09:26.580
of that as D-sharp minor
which is the key of the fugue,

00:09:26.580 --> 00:09:30.330
we have the same key
signature for that.

00:09:30.330 --> 00:09:34.420
When that ends, it's spelled as
D-sharp major, but it sounds--

00:09:34.420 --> 00:09:38.720
we'll hear it as E-flat major which
then leads directly to A-flat major

00:09:38.720 --> 00:09:40.190
which is the key of the Beethoven.

00:09:40.190 --> 00:09:44.140
That sounds complicated
but it sounds very easy

00:09:44.140 --> 00:09:46.800
