This is his penultimate sonata.

00:15:56.430 --> 00:16:04.820
It-- Kind of, it's a step
back from-- in terms of--

00:16:04.820 --> 00:16:08.650
it has this air of
simplicity without being simple

00:16:08.650 --> 00:16:12.930
from what he had done
before if we look at say

00:16:12.930 --> 00:16:17.380 position:56%
like the Hammerklavier's Sonata Opus
106 which was just I think a year,

00:16:17.380 --> 00:16:21.670
a year and a half previously
to the A-flat major composed.

00:16:21.670 --> 00:16:27.790
Before we look at briefly at
how he deals with the fugue,

00:16:27.790 --> 00:16:33.650
I just want to point out that at
this point in Beethoven's life,

00:16:33.650 --> 00:16:37.360
regardless of the state
of his hearing,

00:16:37.360 --> 00:16:39.780
he still has this exceptional
ability

00:16:39.780 --> 00:16:42.140
to orchestrate at the keyboard.

00:16:42.140 --> 00:16:43.590
And I make the statement
about Beethoven,

00:16:43.590 --> 00:16:44.890
but it may as well be saying it

00:16:44.890 --> 00:16:47.410
about every other composer
on this program.

00:16:47.410 --> 00:16:50.690
It doesn't matter-- When I say
orchestrating at the keyboard,

00:16:50.690 --> 00:16:53.120
I don't mean to say like
these are the trumpets,

00:16:53.120 --> 00:16:56.800
these could be the strings or one
could do that and that's fine.

00:16:56.800 --> 00:17:00.350
But, I mean that they treat
the different registers

00:17:00.350 --> 00:17:03.700
and the different types of
sound that one can achieve

00:17:03.700 --> 00:17:09.550
at a given keyboard instrument in
ways that are totally significant

00:17:09.550 --> 00:17:11.940
and dramatically significant.

00:17:11.940 --> 00:17:18.200
So, I just picked one example among
many where Beethoven does this.

00:17:18.200 --> 00:17:23.370
You can see those little pickup
chords, the little grace notes

00:17:23.370 --> 00:17:28.300 position:56%
that precede B2 or the first measure
there, and then they can kind

00:17:28.300 --> 00:17:30.300
of continue through that
second measure that you see.

00:17:30.300 --> 00:17:35.880
Those have to kind of fill
out the sound in those spots.

00:17:35.880 --> 00:17:38.870
But then, he abandons
them and continues up to

00:17:38.870 --> 00:17:41.610
that top note without any support.

00:17:41.610 --> 00:17:45.630
Now, he might have chosen to do
octaves or something like that.

00:17:45.630 --> 00:17:49.740
But it's not-- for him, it wasn't
just a question of building sound,

00:17:49.740 --> 00:17:52.340
it was building a particular
type of sound.

00:17:52.340 --> 00:17:56.750
And what we end up hearing when
you have just a single pitch

00:17:56.750 --> 00:18:02.890 position:56%
at that greater remove from the
base is a very unique sort of sound.

00:18:02.890 --> 00:18:06.660
So, that's just something to
listen for in these pieces.

00:18:06.660 --> 00:18:09.050
It's just the way that they--

00:18:09.050 --> 00:18:11.830
these composers treat sound
is a very thoughtful one.

00:18:11.830 --> 00:18:14.500
Of course, we know that with
Bach especially with Brahms,

00:18:14.500 --> 00:18:16.710
but at the same time,
it's worth pointing

00:18:16.710 --> 00:18:18.820
out because those are
the kinds of details

00:18:18.820 --> 00:18:22.940
that really give life
to the music I think.

00:18:27.390 --> 00:18:31.210
When we look at the
fugue, it comes into play

00:18:31.210 --> 00:18:34.870 position:56%
in an interesting way in the sonata.

00:18:36.090 --> 00:18:40.180
Ostensibly, the work is on three
movements in terms of what you see

00:18:40.180 --> 00:18:45.870
on the page but really, it's
divided into many further.

00:18:45.870 --> 00:18:49.910
Well, it may not further but some,
it depends on how you parse it.

00:18:49.910 --> 00:18:51.790
So, you have the first movement

00:18:51.790 --> 00:18:54.370
and then you have this
characteristic of second movement.

00:18:54.370 --> 00:18:59.040
And then you have this like
adagio and recitative kind

00:18:59.040 --> 00:19:03.470
of vocal quality type of
improvisatory passage that leads

00:19:03.470 --> 00:19:10.000
to this very beautiful arioso,
theme kind of a lugubrious kind

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:12.710
of passage in a whole section.

00:19:12.710 --> 00:19:17.000 position:56%
And this section leads directly to
the first presentation of the fugue.

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:20.270
And he marks it Fuga.

00:19:20.270 --> 00:19:23.510
Maybe we can play--
this is track 11.

00:19:23.510 --> 00:19:29.040
[ Music ]

00:19:29.040 --> 00:19:34.300 position:56%
So, I wanted you to hear that
transition that leads into it first.

00:19:34.300 --> 00:19:36.200
That's the end of the arioso.

00:19:36.200 --> 00:19:40.080 position:56%
We didn't have time to hear the
full thing but we will a little bit.

00:19:40.080 --> 00:19:46.780
And now, compare that
with this really, I think,

00:19:46.780 --> 00:19:50.760
just a kind of a magical
but simple moment that leads

00:19:50.760 --> 00:19:53.280
to the return of the fugue.

00:19:53.280 --> 00:19:54.820
But this time, it's in version.

00:19:54.820 --> 00:19:58.510
He even labels it such
so that we don't miss it.

00:19:58.510 --> 00:20:06.040
[ Music ]

00:20:06.040 --> 00:20:09.070
I wanted to let that
play on just a little bit

00:20:09.070 --> 00:20:13.860
so that you could hear how little
tiny ideas start to get parsed

00:20:13.860 --> 00:20:17.800
and then get reinvented and
turned into something else.

00:20:17.800 --> 00:20:20.400
They're-- Which is a very
a bit of anything to do

00:20:20.400 --> 00:20:22.890
but it's also a very
fugal thing to do.

00:20:22.890 --> 00:20:26.980
It's part of what this is about.

00:20:28.780 --> 00:20:33.530
Building something out of
something that's recognizable

00:20:33.530 --> 00:20:38.280
but can have many different
types of utility.

00:20:38.280 --> 00:20:45.010
What's, of course, the most
obvious difference about this

00:20:45.010 --> 00:20:46.550
versus say though, the Bach fugues

00:20:46.550 --> 00:20:49.690
that you'll hear preceding
the Beethoven is the way

00:20:49.690 --> 00:20:53.310
that it's split now
into, at the easiest way

00:20:53.310 --> 00:20:55.010
of looking at, four
different sections.

00:20:55.010 --> 00:21:00.870
So we have the arioso then we have
initial presentation of the fugue.

00:21:00.870 --> 00:21:06.390
Then we have a return to the arioso
and a much more impassioned form.

00:21:06.390 --> 00:21:10.590
And then a return to the fugue
with the, in this case, inverted.

00:21:10.590 --> 00:21:14.360
And then, some people think
that it's-- you might call it,

00:21:14.360 --> 00:21:16.280
at the very end, a different
thing because it moves

00:21:16.280 --> 00:21:20.320
out of fugal textures but it's
still basically the summation

00:21:20.320 --> 00:21:22.380
and there's an arch to it.

00:21:22.380 --> 00:21:25.730
And that's going to be important

00:21:25.730 --> 00:21:31.270 position:56%
with Brahms too is understanding
this arch that people are going for.

00:21:31.270 --> 00:21:35.560 position:56%
So it becomes less about just making
some sort of academic statement

00:21:35.560 --> 00:21:38.850
as it is about making some
sort of a musical journey

00:21:38.850 --> 00:21:42.190
in helping the listener
to appreciate it.

00:21:42.190 --> 00:21:48.810
So, moving ahead, 40 or so years,
we get to the-- I'm sorry--

00:21:48.810 --> 00:21:51.960
we get to the opening of the
Brahms Handel variations.

00:21:51.960 --> 00:21:55.370
This manuscript dates from 1861.

00:21:55.370 --> 00:21:59.420 position:56%
And at this point, it's not
exactly named in a way that we know.

00:21:59.420 --> 00:22:03.070
It's just the Variations and
Fugue on a Theme by Handel.

00:22:03.070 --> 00:22:09.580
Instead, it says Variationen
für eine liebe Freundin.

00:22:09.580 --> 00:22:13.450
So, this is for Clara Schumann.

00:22:13.450 --> 00:22:16.310
Yeah. I'm sorry.

00:22:16.310 --> 00:22:22.300
Yeah. So the-- who had--
who performed it and--

00:22:22.300 --> 00:22:26.720
but not exactly up to Brahms
level of expectations.

00:22:26.720 --> 00:22:30.670
Brahms also played this for
her but Clara had to do it

00:22:30.670 --> 00:22:33.250
in difficult circumstances
where she had a limited amount

00:22:33.250 --> 00:22:35.090
of time to actually perform.

00:22:35.090 --> 00:22:37.330
I think she did both of
the piano quartets as well,

00:22:37.330 --> 00:22:41.750
but definitely Opus 25 which comes
right after the set of Opus 24.

00:22:41.750 --> 00:22:45.040
And she learned these pieces
very quickly and, of course,

00:22:45.040 --> 00:22:48.740
eventually did a very good job with
them but it cost this small falling

00:22:48.740 --> 00:22:51.560
out for a brief period of time.

00:22:51.560 --> 00:22:53.040
Brahms at this point is 28.

00:22:53.040 --> 00:22:58.340
So, he's already accomplished a
lot but he's not quite at the level

00:22:58.340 --> 00:23:05.030
where he's got the great kind
of recognition that he wants

00:23:05.030 --> 00:23:07.700
for himself and to-- I don't mean
that in terms of public recognition

00:23:07.700 --> 00:23:09.690
but I mean it in terms of feeling

00:23:09.690 --> 00:23:12.240
that he has complete
command of what he's doing.

00:23:12.240 --> 00:23:18.180
And this is getting back to that
idea of mastering one's art.

00:23:19.540 --> 00:23:23.530
So one way to do that is to kind
of, you know, deal with the past

00:23:23.530 --> 00:23:26.960 position:56%
by encountering the forms and Brahms
does this repeatedly throughout

00:23:26.960 --> 00:23:28.260
his career.

00:23:28.260 --> 00:23:31.450
You know, one of the most famous
examples being the finally movement

00:23:31.450 --> 00:23:35.600
of the fourth symphony where it
takes on a passacaglia and kind

00:23:35.600 --> 00:23:38.820
of creates this great movement
out of it which is, you know,

00:23:38.820 --> 00:23:42.430
it's interesting because it's--
it is an achievement but it's also

00:23:42.430 --> 00:23:44.920
in some ways, it's an
easy way to have some sort

00:23:44.920 --> 00:23:48.170
of basic structure
that you can work with.

00:23:48.170 --> 00:23:51.300
And something similar is happening
with the Handel variations.

00:23:51.300 --> 00:23:55.590
And what I mean by that is that
the theme itself which is an aria

00:23:55.590 --> 00:23:59.450 position:56%
from a sweet, that Handel composing,

00:23:59.450 --> 00:24:03.500
he actually wrote in
the same key B-flat.

00:24:03.500 --> 00:24:06.760
And he composed I think
five variations

00:24:06.760 --> 00:24:10.290 position:56%
on this aria in that original sweet.

00:24:10.290 --> 00:24:16.480
It has the same basic periodic
structure and Brahms maintains

00:24:16.480 --> 00:24:21.570
that almost without exception for
the entire duration of the work.

00:24:21.570 --> 00:24:25.060
So, when we look at it
here, we're just setting

00:24:25.060 --> 00:24:29.450
that Brahms has here just that you
see the theme at the beginning.

00:24:29.450 --> 00:24:31.990
It's basically four
measures repeated.

00:24:31.990 --> 00:24:34.810
And then, a second group
of four measures repeated.

00:24:34.810 --> 00:24:39.590
And it's quite ornamented
but we see right away

00:24:39.590 --> 00:24:43.620
that Brahms embraces
this ornamentation

00:24:43.620 --> 00:24:46.980
in a way that's very different
than the way that Handel did.

00:24:46.980 --> 00:24:52.550
So, if we just look at the
particulars of towards the end

00:24:52.550 --> 00:24:57.020
of Variation One in the Handel
versus the end of Variation One

00:24:57.020 --> 00:24:59.880
in the Brahms, I'm not
meaning to say one is better

00:24:59.880 --> 00:25:01.600
than the other or anything
like that.

00:25:01.600 --> 00:25:04.220
First of all, they're
quite, you know,

00:25:04.220 --> 00:25:06.080
distinct in so many different ways.

00:25:06.080 --> 00:25:09.510
But rather that they treat the
material, you can still see

00:25:09.510 --> 00:25:14.880
that they're kind of engaging in
the same argument but already,

00:25:14.880 --> 00:25:18.410
Brahms is moving quite a bit away
and emphasizing those details

00:25:18.410 --> 00:25:22.920
like the ornamentation and whatnot.

00:25:25.600 --> 00:25:33.330
So, one of the great pleasures of
being able to look at autograph--

00:25:33.330 --> 00:25:37.430
holograph manuscripts by
composers who we can't speak

00:25:37.430 --> 00:25:41.820
to now is we get a
window into their process,

00:25:41.820 --> 00:25:47.140
and this particular piece
offered us a few options.

00:25:47.140 --> 00:25:53.170
I was able to look-- to meet with
Pierre-Laurent Aimard yesterday

00:25:53.170 --> 00:25:57.660
to talk over a number of these
different changes that were made

00:25:57.660 --> 00:26:00.200
to the score, and it was just
a great pleasure to be able

00:26:00.200 --> 00:26:02.470
to look at this in detail.

00:26:02.470 --> 00:26:07.970
Because it's not always just, you
know, once you have a fair copy

00:26:07.970 --> 00:26:12.580
which is what this basically is,
it's pretty much a done piece.

00:26:12.580 --> 00:26:16.180
And so, composers will sometimes
put in different dynamic markings.

00:26:16.180 --> 00:26:19.000
Maybe change a tempo here or there.

00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:22.020
I think actually on
the previous-- oops--

00:26:22.020 --> 00:26:24.880
in the previous, this first
page, you can see that, you know,

00:26:24.880 --> 00:26:28.280
he has put in a second ending
in pencil at the very end

00:26:28.280 --> 00:26:30.170
on the bottom right
side of the screen.

00:26:30.170 --> 00:26:32.040
You can kind of see that pencil.

00:26:32.040 --> 00:26:35.300
He would do this throughout this
and it's just a way of saying,

00:26:35.300 --> 00:26:37.890
I need to do something
differently to transition

00:26:37.890 --> 00:26:41.420
between movements or
between variations.

00:26:41.420 --> 00:26:43.740
But sometimes, they become
a bit more significant.

00:26:43.740 --> 00:26:45.620
I'm just going to point
out a couple of this.

00:26:45.620 --> 00:26:47.730
But just because I think
it's an interesting thing.

00:26:47.730 --> 00:26:50.610
And I think it's important to
see these as living documents

00:26:50.610 --> 00:26:55.350
and not just, you know, these
notes on the page that I've come

00:26:55.350 --> 00:26:59.320
down from ages past that, you know,
these are things that were workable

00:26:59.320 --> 00:27:01.510
and then, you know, Brahms might
have changed his mind later.

00:27:01.510 --> 00:27:03.870
In fact, he did in certain cases.

00:27:03.870 --> 00:27:09.130
So, at the end of Variation
Eight, at the very top right--

00:27:09.130 --> 00:27:11.110
I don't know if you
can see it too well.

00:27:11.110 --> 00:27:16.250
But what you should see is some
pencilled-in notes underneath

00:27:16.250 --> 00:27:18.250
on the top right.

00:27:18.250 --> 00:27:23.670 position:56%
Basically, those are-- he originally
had just same repeated notes

00:27:23.670 --> 00:27:26.130
in the left-hand, I
keep going on and on.

00:27:26.130 --> 00:27:28.990
But instead, he decides
to have them go

00:27:28.990 --> 00:27:31.150
up an octave and up another octave.

00:27:31.150 --> 00:27:33.090
This is the kind of
orchestrational decision

00:27:33.090 --> 00:27:35.330 position:56%
where it doesn't change the harmony.

00:27:35.330 --> 00:27:37.130
It just doesn't change
that sort of a thing,

00:27:37.130 --> 00:27:41.980
but it does change the affect
and the motion of the piece.

00:27:41.980 --> 00:27:45.060
So that's one example
of a type of change.

00:27:45.060 --> 00:27:51.310
Another major example is
changing the order entirely

00:27:51.310 --> 00:27:53.590
of the variations.

00:27:53.590 --> 00:27:56.650
It's been said of this piece
and other variation sets

00:27:56.650 --> 00:28:00.680 position:56%
that sometimes you can just-- you
could just arbitrarily take them out

00:28:00.680 --> 00:28:05.490
and put them into a different order
and no one would be the wiser.

00:28:05.490 --> 00:28:09.210
And maybe that's true, in
certain cases, each one--

00:28:09.210 --> 00:28:11.030
each variation is sort of an--

00:28:11.030 --> 00:28:15.830
a clear set idea onto itself,
that's absolutely true.

00:28:15.830 --> 00:28:22.720
But there's also this very clear
directionality that is dealt

00:28:22.720 --> 00:28:26.780
within particular ways that
are more or less effective.

00:28:26.780 --> 00:28:28.830
And Brahms sensed this
when he was looking

00:28:28.830 --> 00:28:31.870
at this particular
sequence of variations.

00:28:31.870 --> 00:28:38.070
So, coming out of Variation 14,
you have this very strong movement

00:28:38.070 --> 00:28:41.920
and use of sixth in the right hand
especially, you'll kind of see

00:28:41.920 --> 00:28:46.490
at the top of the page, you'll see
those sixths going back and forth.

00:28:46.490 --> 00:28:51.590
What happens when-- I'm not
sure how practical this will be.

00:28:51.590 --> 00:28:55.670
This will be on these
two by the way.

00:28:55.670 --> 00:29:01.040
What happens is that you start to
get a sort of back and forth thing

00:29:01.040 --> 00:29:05.260
if you're not careful about how you
handle the order of the variations.

00:29:05.260 --> 00:29:08.520
So, the way that Brahms
had it originally--

00:29:08.520 --> 00:29:12.240
We'll just hear a little
bit of that.

00:29:12.240 --> 00:29:13.540
I'm not sure if this will work.

00:29:13.540 --> 00:29:19.510
But starting in track 15,
this would be Variation 14.

00:29:19.510 --> 00:29:24.040
[ Music ]

00:29:24.040 --> 00:29:25.920
I'll come back to that shortly.

00:29:25.920 --> 00:29:27.490
That was just a snippet from each

00:29:27.490 --> 00:29:30.730
of these four variations
in their original order.

00:29:30.730 --> 00:29:33.750
Now, one of the things that
we see, and that's going

00:29:33.750 --> 00:29:36.830
on to the 17th Variation.

00:29:36.830 --> 00:29:41.560
In the new ordering,
Brahms takes advantage

00:29:41.560 --> 00:29:43.570
of what he'd actually
originally written.

00:29:43.570 --> 00:29:46.490
So we have those sixths that I
pointed out just a moment ago.

00:29:46.490 --> 00:29:49.480
This is at the end of Variation 14.

00:29:49.480 --> 00:29:53.620
Then we have this, what I'm
referring to in the title there

00:29:53.620 --> 00:29:56.890
in terms of the hunting which is
basically interval contraction

00:29:56.890 --> 00:29:58.190
and expansion.

00:29:58.190 --> 00:30:01.850
You'll often hear this but because
of the way the horns were tuned,

00:30:01.850 --> 00:30:05.040
where you have as you go
higher, you get closer together.

00:30:05.040 --> 00:30:08.190
And so you might start with
an octave then fifths and,

00:30:08.190 --> 00:30:09.700
you know, getting smaller.

00:30:09.700 --> 00:30:13.450
So we have a third at the top
and then coming back down.

00:30:13.450 --> 00:30:16.670
In this case, you have the
reverse at the end of Variation 14,

00:30:16.670 --> 00:30:17.970
and that's the part I've labeled

00:30:17.970 --> 00:30:21.790
in the second measure interval
contraction and expansion.

00:30:21.790 --> 00:30:27.830
Then, if you go directly
into the new Variation 15,

00:30:27.830 --> 00:30:33.530
you see that you get the tonal
inversion of that material,

00:30:33.530 --> 00:30:34.830
and that's also labeled--

00:30:34.830 --> 00:30:39.220
that's labeled now interval
expansion and then contraction.

00:30:39.220 --> 00:30:43.260
So, you start to have this
actual-- it was already there.

00:30:43.260 --> 00:30:45.950 position:56%
He'd already written the
variations in that particular order,

00:30:45.950 --> 00:30:47.960
but this brings out a
particular relationship

00:30:47.960 --> 00:30:50.860
and especially the thirds and sixth

00:30:50.860 --> 00:30:52.440
which are also inversions
of each other.

00:30:52.440 --> 00:30:55.370
If you have a sixth and you
put this sixth underneath,

00:30:55.370 --> 00:30:58.790
it turns into a third.

00:30:58.790 --> 00:31:00.510
He takes advantage of that in a way

00:31:00.510 --> 00:31:04.780
that makes the variations move
together a bit more smoothly.

00:31:04.780 --> 00:31:12.900
Additionally, it has the
advantage now of ending perfectly

00:31:12.900 --> 00:31:18.090
into Variation 17-- I'm trying
not to get this confused.

00:31:18.090 --> 00:31:21.660
To where-- With the new
end of Variation 16,

00:31:21.660 --> 00:31:25.070
it leads very smoothly
into variation 17.

00:31:25.070 --> 00:31:29.120
So, instead of talking
about that ad nauseum here,

00:31:29.120 --> 00:31:30.550
why don't we just listen to that?

00:31:30.550 --> 00:31:34.200
So this will be starting
from 15 and we'll just listen

00:31:34.200 --> 00:31:37.510
through to the beginning of 18.

00:31:37.510 --> 00:31:40.060
[ Music ]

00:31:40.060 --> 00:31:43.120
So when you hear without
that delayed,

00:31:43.120 --> 00:31:46.880
it does move in smoothly
into that new variation.

00:31:46.880 --> 00:31:49.510
So those types of decisions
are made at various stages

00:31:49.510 --> 00:31:50.870
in the compositional process.

00:31:50.870 --> 00:31:53.750
And these cases are
fairly late stage.

00:31:53.750 --> 00:31:55.810
It's just important to
note and interesting

00:31:55.810 --> 00:32:00.140
to consider what it would have
been like if you hadn't done that.

00:32:00.140 --> 00:32:01.590
I don't think that people
would have thought less

00:32:01.590 --> 00:32:03.040
to the piece to be honest.

00:32:03.040 --> 00:32:06.630
But at the same time, one
has the sense that, yeah,

00:32:06.630 --> 00:32:08.070
that seemed like the right move.

00:32:08.070 --> 00:32:11.550
Sometimes, you find an earlier
version that composers do

00:32:11.550 --> 00:32:15.900
and you think, wow, I wish that he
or she just kept it the way it was

00:32:15.900 --> 00:32:19.090
because that was kind of maybe,
a little bit more effective.

00:32:19.090 --> 00:32:22.770
But, this is kind of one of the
fun things about being able to look

00:32:22.770 --> 00:32:25.070
at these older manuscripts.

00:32:28.680 --> 00:32:32.310
Some of these changes that
composers make don't make it

00:32:32.310 --> 00:32:33.610
into the final version.

00:32:33.610 --> 00:32:36.840
So, it's not always-- you know,
when you look and talk about urtext

00:32:36.840 --> 00:32:40.350
and like this final
word kind of volumes

00:32:40.350 --> 00:32:43.860 position:56%
that people put together these days
which are important in their own way

00:32:43.860 --> 00:32:49.540
for sure, they don't always
embody some very interesting ideas

00:32:49.540 --> 00:32:52.240
that the composer might have
put down at the beginning.

00:32:52.240 --> 00:32:55.910
And this is one that was just
pointed out to me yesterday

00:32:55.910 --> 00:33:00.870
in that talk which is that at the
top here and measure-- I'm sorry--

00:33:00.870 --> 00:33:04.160
at Variation 21, you have--
he wrote in Pizzicato.

00:33:04.160 --> 00:33:08.430
And he's pointing to
the grace notes.

00:33:08.430 --> 00:33:09.730
And why is this important?

00:33:09.730 --> 00:33:11.600
Because it's an orchestrational
detail.

00:33:11.600 --> 00:33:14.220
He doesn't mean you're going to
reach in and pluck the string,

00:33:14.220 --> 00:33:15.570
although that would be impressive.

00:33:15.570 --> 00:33:19.790
And I have to say, I don't dare
any pianists to take that on

00:33:19.790 --> 00:33:23.830
but what's important about
that word with respect

00:33:23.830 --> 00:33:27.310
to the grace notes is that's where
you get the thematic reference.

00:33:27.310 --> 00:33:29.120
The theme is in the grace notes.

00:33:29.120 --> 00:33:32.320
So he's saying, there's a
color choice that you can make

00:33:32.320 --> 00:33:36.310
in the way-- or the way that
you articulate those grace notes

00:33:36.310 --> 00:33:39.400
that would allow it to
sing it in a particular way

00:33:39.400 --> 00:33:42.460
that makes it-- the
theme more clear.

00:33:42.460 --> 00:33:44.890
So, those types of things
are very interesting I think

00:33:44.890 --> 00:33:46.230
to be able to see.

00:33:46.230 --> 00:33:47.950
And then, that's what
we can learn form this

00:33:47.950 --> 00:33:50.880
that you won't find
in a modern edition.

00:33:50.880 --> 00:33:56.700
Sometimes you do as footnotes
but not all the time.

00:33:58.290 --> 00:34:05.010 position:56%
Another case that I think is
worth-taking note of is that the way

00:34:05.010 --> 00:34:09.850 position:56%
that a composer writes especially if
it's handwritten is very evocative

00:34:09.850 --> 00:34:14.230
of what they might be asking
for in the music itself.

00:34:14.230 --> 00:34:15.530
That's not always true.

00:34:15.530 --> 00:34:17.430
There's plenty of passionate
music that looks

00:34:17.430 --> 00:34:20.490
about as stayed as one can have it.

00:34:20.490 --> 00:34:24.780
But there's this passage work
that is leading to the final fugue

00:34:24.780 --> 00:34:30.210
in the Brahms where he-- clearly,
it starts to have this sweep

00:34:30.210 --> 00:34:32.640
to the way that he's writing.

00:34:32.640 --> 00:34:36.370
And you can see this especially
in the Variation 24 at the bottom

00:34:36.370 --> 00:34:40.130
of this page, but also leading
into it from the Variation 23

00:34:40.130 --> 00:34:44.200 position:56%
which is very much the same type of
material, just a slightly different.

00:34:44.200 --> 00:34:50.100
And all I'm referring to really
are just the way that it looks.

00:34:50.100 --> 00:34:53.000
It matches the way that it sounds.

00:34:53.000 --> 00:34:55.390
Let me think-- what's
that-- that's going to be--

00:34:55.390 --> 00:34:58.510
Can you play just the
beginning of track 25?

00:34:58.510 --> 00:35:02.660
[ Music ]

00:35:02.660 --> 00:35:06.970
So you get the sense of sweep, the
sense of motion and you see this

00:35:06.970 --> 00:35:09.740
and there's other material
that has a certain similarity

00:35:09.740 --> 00:35:11.660
to this earlier in
the variation set.

00:35:11.660 --> 00:35:13.380
But it's not-- it doesn't
have the same sort

00:35:13.380 --> 00:35:17.480
of handwriting signature
that this does.

00:35:17.480 --> 00:35:19.630
One can read too much
into that, of course.

00:35:19.630 --> 00:35:22.350
You might have been just getting
tired and just ready to be done

00:35:22.350 --> 00:35:24.900
with it because at this point,
it was just copying it out to.

00:35:24.900 --> 00:35:29.220
So it wasn't like in the midst of
the compositional process probably.

00:35:29.220 --> 00:35:32.440
But it is something
that you tend to see

00:35:32.440 --> 00:35:36.100
and it's another interesting
component.

00:35:36.100 --> 00:35:42.120
When we get to the fugue,
there's an interesting kind

00:35:42.120 --> 00:35:45.220
of moment that's reminiscent to me
or Schumann, especially Schumann

00:35:45.220 --> 00:35:48.850
of the Symphonic Etudes,
the 25th Variation here.

00:35:50.040 --> 00:35:52.990
And all I want to point
out about the fugue here,

00:35:52.990 --> 00:35:57.120
because it's a big fugue,
it's a good five minutes or so

00:35:57.120 --> 00:36:03.860 position:56%
and it's a great closer, is that you
start to see again the same types

00:36:03.860 --> 00:36:08.300
of techniques that are being used
by both Bach and Beethoven before.

00:36:08.300 --> 00:36:12.800
Namely, taking a small cellular
idea and then expanding it

00:36:12.800 --> 00:36:17.380
to produce a larger phrase, and
then using those cellular ideas

00:36:17.380 --> 00:36:19.840
as accompanimental
[phonetic] figuration.

00:36:19.840 --> 00:36:23.980
Just like in the Bach in the
A-flat prelude, it wasn't a fugue

00:36:23.980 --> 00:36:28.000
but there's that little turn idea,
that neighbor note idea that was--

00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:30.890
that went back and forth
that was a little snippet

00:36:30.890 --> 00:36:34.630
that was already recognizable
when you'd hear.

00:36:34.630 --> 00:36:36.510
You have the same exact thing here,

00:36:36.510 --> 00:36:40.100
almost verbatim just
inverted in the Brahms.

00:36:40.100 --> 00:36:41.880
And so that starts to be used.

00:36:41.880 --> 00:36:47.270
You can see-- Well, it's-- it
will be better just to hear it

00:36:47.270 --> 00:36:50.660
when we get to it and just
hear how they're put together.

00:36:50.660 --> 00:36:57.300
The other point I'd like to
make about the Brahms' fugue

00:36:57.300 --> 00:37:01.270
in particular and, it also applies
to the Beethoven and to some

00:37:01.270 --> 00:37:08.160
of the Bach fugues as well,
is that of the issues--

00:37:08.160 --> 00:37:12.100 position:56%
it starts to become a drama-- a case
of what is important dramatically

00:37:12.100 --> 00:37:14.460 position:56%
to the music to push things forward.

00:37:14.460 --> 00:37:21.840
And Brahms at this point, I feel
that there's a great sense of ease

00:37:21.840 --> 00:37:24.240
with which he writes
this fugue that it feels

00:37:24.240 --> 00:37:28.890 position:56%
like this is exactly what it needs
to be for him and it encompasses him

00:37:28.890 --> 00:37:31.770 position:56%
as a pianist, as well as a composer.

00:37:31.770 --> 00:37:35.710
And this was I think one of the
most important moves for Brahms.

00:37:35.710 --> 00:37:41.740
Because as a pianist,
he was able to kind

00:37:41.740 --> 00:37:43.570
of make the fugue his
own in this way.

00:37:43.570 --> 00:37:48.140
So what you'll hear are
figurations and different types

00:37:48.140 --> 00:37:53.230
of sonorities put together with
the recognizable fugal elements

00:37:53.230 --> 00:37:56.100
that start to take on
a life of their own,

00:37:56.100 --> 00:38:00.220
as almost like their own
little cellular motivic ideas

00:38:00.220 --> 00:38:05.230
that could even be sort
of like a textural subject

00:38:05.230 --> 00:38:06.540
or something like that.

00:38:06.540 --> 00:38:09.770
I'm not saying that he treats it
exactly in a sort of academically

00:38:09.770 --> 00:38:12.250
that way, but you do
start to get that feeling.

00:38:12.250 --> 00:38:15.380
And eventually, you start to
forget about the fact that you're

00:38:15.380 --> 00:38:19.850
in the midst of this kind
of learned composition

00:38:19.850 --> 00:38:22.070
and just hear it as music.

00:38:22.070 --> 00:38:25.130
And I think that that's also
something that I suspect happens

00:38:25.130 --> 00:38:29.260
to a lot of us when we listen to
a fugue, is that we kind of think

00:38:29.260 --> 00:38:34.150
at the beginning, OK, there's
a voice and there's an answer,

00:38:34.150 --> 00:38:37.600
and then it comes back maybe at the
same pitch or something like that.

00:38:37.600 --> 00:38:41.780
And we follow it through this
exposition, but at some point,

00:38:41.780 --> 00:38:45.750
we start to just appreciate the way
that these voices are interacting

00:38:45.750 --> 00:38:49.490
in a way that just
makes for great music.

00:38:49.490 --> 00:38:52.830
So with that, I'd like to just
go ahead and close and be happy

00:38:52.830 --> 00:38:56.820
to take any questions
you might have.

00:38:56.820 --> 00:39:03.210
And if you could just wait for--

