00:39:15.980 --> 00:39:17.280
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:39:17.280 --> 00:39:18.580
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Yeah.

00:39:18.580 --> 00:39:19.880
&gt;&gt; The way you did.

00:39:19.880 --> 00:39:21.180
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Yes.

00:39:21.180 --> 00:39:23.930
It just depends on the person
and the access that they have.

00:39:23.930 --> 00:39:28.490
So, one of the issues is that,
you know, often, we have our--

00:39:28.490 --> 00:39:32.970 position:56%
we might have a version of the piece
that we have back home that we used,

00:39:32.970 --> 00:39:35.250
you know, when we were kids
maybe or something like that.

00:39:35.250 --> 00:39:39.260
And eventually, you start to look
for other editions maybe edited

00:39:39.260 --> 00:39:41.770
by different people who you admire.

00:39:41.770 --> 00:39:45.870
But if you're at a professional
level and you're performing,

00:39:45.870 --> 00:39:48.410
you tend to want to make
your own decision as much

00:39:48.410 --> 00:39:50.730
as you can especially when dealing

00:39:50.730 --> 00:39:54.040
with these particular
types of pieces.

00:39:54.040 --> 00:39:56.720
And so, oftentimes, performers--

00:39:56.720 --> 00:39:58.510
there are performer
scholars that will go through

00:39:58.510 --> 00:40:01.600
and do their own research and
they're-- I think that what they--

00:40:01.600 --> 00:40:05.630
and, of course, I can't speak
for anybody but I do think

00:40:05.630 --> 00:40:10.030
that there is a sense in which
they arrive at the conclusion

00:40:10.030 --> 00:40:13.870
that here's a way that I
want to present this music

00:40:13.870 --> 00:40:18.680
that I believe is faithful to
an idea that was perhaps held

00:40:18.680 --> 00:40:23.260
by the composer but not necessarily
fidelity to a particular text.

00:40:23.260 --> 00:40:24.800
And just like I was
saying with the Brahms,

00:40:24.800 --> 00:40:28.410
you have all these notes here
that are in Brahms handwriting

00:40:28.410 --> 00:40:32.030
that did not make it
into a final edition.

00:40:32.030 --> 00:40:36.630
So, OK, maybe he though better
of it and took it out later.

00:40:36.630 --> 00:40:39.210
But there is something about
maybe an idea that are kernel

00:40:39.210 --> 00:40:41.670
of something that is worth-keeping.

00:40:41.670 --> 00:40:45.270
And so, I think it's up to each
musician to make a decision

00:40:45.270 --> 00:40:47.330
about what they'd like to do.

00:40:47.330 --> 00:40:50.910
And last thing I'd say about that
is that, you know, one of the goals

00:40:50.910 --> 00:40:54.740
of libraries and other
institutions is to try to make--

00:40:54.740 --> 00:40:58.370
the people who or the institutions
that hold these manuscripts is

00:40:58.370 --> 00:41:01.920
to try to make them as available
to those people as possible.

00:41:01.920 --> 00:41:04.250
And so for instance, this
particular manuscript,

00:41:04.250 --> 00:41:08.720
anybody here can go online to
our Performing Arts Encyclopedia

00:41:08.720 --> 00:41:11.960
and take a look at it yourself
and you can download images.

00:41:11.960 --> 00:41:14.320
Now, we don't have all of
our manuscripts up that way

00:41:14.320 --> 00:41:18.700
but that's an-- a way to make
them accessible to others.

00:41:18.700 --> 00:41:20.000
&gt;&gt; All right.

