00:46:24.210 --> 00:46:31.460
One more.

00:46:31.460 --> 00:46:34.980 position:56%
&gt;&gt; You didn't go into the origins
of the fugue and most people I think

00:46:34.980 --> 00:46:42.470
in the most elementary way think of
it as developing out of the round.

00:46:42.470 --> 00:46:47.240
And here, I know I do, I hear
the round in almost every fugue

00:46:47.240 --> 00:46:49.150
and that's the way I approach it.

00:46:49.150 --> 00:46:51.190
Could you talk a little
bit about that?

00:46:51.190 --> 00:46:55.100
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: That's a very
complicated issue and there's--

00:46:55.100 --> 00:47:00.060
so there's a history going way
before Bach's time in terms

00:47:00.060 --> 00:47:04.780
of what-- where a fugue comes
from, things like the Ricercar,

00:47:04.780 --> 00:47:08.080
all these other types
of predecessors.

00:47:08.080 --> 00:47:12.230 position:56%
But ultimately, what they're founded
on and I think it'd be better

00:47:12.230 --> 00:47:16.810
to look to somebody who's more of
a scholar in that area than I am.

00:47:16.810 --> 00:47:22.670 position:56%
But ultimately, what they're founded
on are relationships between ideas

00:47:22.670 --> 00:47:26.440
of counted point and
imitation on those types

00:47:26.440 --> 00:47:28.710
of things and imitative behaviors.

00:47:28.710 --> 00:47:31.570
So, certain types of rules
start to develop over--

00:47:31.570 --> 00:47:35.120
when I say rules, I'm not saying
necessarily written-down rules

00:47:35.120 --> 00:47:40.220
but just rules that tend
to work in practice.

00:47:40.220 --> 00:47:43.360
Over time, those develop and
eventually become codified

00:47:43.360 --> 00:47:46.670
by different theorists at
different points thinking

00:47:46.670 --> 00:47:49.630
of the Gradus ad Parnassum or
things like that where, you know,

00:47:49.630 --> 00:47:55.920
people are trying to come to
grips with what's happening.

00:47:55.920 --> 00:48:01.240
Not necessarily providing
a groundwork for what--

00:48:01.240 --> 00:48:03.100
how people should produce.

00:48:03.100 --> 00:48:05.000
But eventually, you
do get that as well

00:48:05.000 --> 00:48:09.280
and so there's this
lengthy process development

00:48:09.280 --> 00:48:13.490
that is not a singular
branch on a tree, I think.

00:48:13.490 --> 00:48:16.660
I think that there are lots
of different approaches that--

00:48:16.660 --> 00:48:21.200
and even today, you know,
people still write fugues.

00:48:21.200 --> 00:48:26.060
But it's, you know, maybe most
of them tend to be traceable

00:48:26.060 --> 00:48:30.030
to the 18th Century in terms
of where they're coming from,

00:48:30.030 --> 00:48:33.090
in terms of what they
identify as a fugue proper.

00:48:33.090 --> 00:48:38.260
But, I think that other
traditions are also represented.

00:48:38.260 --> 00:48:43.510
So, sorry, I'm not able
simply address that but.

